  <text xml:lang="ta" type="edition">
    <body>
      <div xml:id="NA108-kiḷavi">
        <p type="edition">itu varaiyātu neṭuṅ kāla vantu oḻukal āṟṟāḷāyt tōḻi talaimakaḷ āṟṟāmai kūṟi varaivu kaṭāyatu.</p>
        <p type="translation" xml:lang="en">This is how the confidante, who was unable to bear [HIS] coming for a long time without marrying, asked for marriage by speaking about the lack of strength in HER.</p>
      </div>
      <div xml:id="NA108">
        <lg type="edition">
<l>            malaiyayaṟ kalitta maiyā rēṉaṟ</l>
<l>            ṟuṇaiyiṟ ṟīrnta kaṭuṅkaṇ yāṉai</l>
<l>            yaṇaiyak kaṇṭa vaṅkuṭik kuṟavar</l>
<l>            kaṇaiyar kiṇaiyar kaipuṉai kavaṇar</l>
<l>            viḷiyar puṟakkuṭi yārkku nāṭa </l>
<l>            paḻakiya pakaiyum piriviṉ ṉātē</l>
<l>            mukaiyē rilaṅkeyiṟ ṟiṉṉakai maṭantai</l>
<l>            cuṭarpurai tirunutal pacappat</l>
<l>            toṭarpiyāṅku viṭṭaṉai nōkō yāṉē.</l>
    </lg>
       <lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">
<l>O man from a land,</l>
<l rend="indent2">where the hill people with [their] pretty hamlets,</l>
<l rend="indent">who had seen a fierce-eyed elephant that quit [its] companions, touch</l>
<l rend="indent">the millet fed on the black [clouds]<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">mai ār</term>: or can this simply refer to the dark and presumably healthy colour of the ripening millet? In that case <term xml:lang="ta">kalitta</term> should go with <term xml:lang="ta">ēṉal</term>. One would, however, want parallels.</note> that grew on the nearby mountain,</l>
<l rend="indent2">are making noise near [their] outer homes, some calling out,</l>
<l rend="indent2">some with arrows, or with Kiṇai drums, or with slings worn in the hand,</l>
<l>– even enmity of old [is] unpleasant to separate.<note place="foot">This line looks like the allusion to and aphorism on how one gets even used to one’s enemies, let alone the ones one loves.</note></l>
<l>How could you let go of [her] attachment,</l>
<l rend="indent2">so that the sunlike(?)<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">cuṭar</term> is here explained by T.V.G. as a 'crescent moon', which would be indeed the comparison to be expected for the forehead, but in all other places encountered so far it means the sun. There are two parallels in the NA where the <term xml:lang="ta">nutal</term> is connected with <term xml:lang="ta">cuṭar</term> (NA 208.4, 245.11).</note> brilliance faded on the forehead</l>
<l rend="indent3">of the girl with pleasing smile and bud-like shining teeth?</l>
<l rend="indent4">Ah, I ache.</l>
        </lg>
         </div>
